<title>Family Economics -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center>
<center>
[Go to the <A HREF="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/wgw-forum/ac/dispatch.cgi/thf-cyber/">Forum</A>][<a href="/townhall/wgw-forum/ac/dispatch.cgi/_user/addForm/short">Register</A> -- Free!][<a href="/heritage/cyberp/cybarch.html">Column Archive]</a><p>

<h2><i>Family Economics:  What to Expect for Your Infant's First-Year Costs</i></h2>
by <a href="/heritage/cyberbio.html">Karen Czarnecki Miller</a><br>
October 7, 1996
</center><p>
<blockquote>
<table width=80% border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=10>
<tr valign=top>
<td><img src="/heritage/miller.gif" align=left hspace=2></a></td>
<td>

<b><i>Note to Users:</i></b> After a hectic summer of projects, the CyberPersonality area is back in business. We will begin posting information and columns on a weekly basis, so check back again soon! 
<p> 
	As any working parent knows, having children can be a costly adventure. But has anyone put a figure on what the average costs per child are in 1995 as compared with 1960?  Of course!  Your hard tax dollars are at work once again.  The US federal government, and a few other sources,  have come up with a few statistics that any expecting parent or current parent needs to know:
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<blockquote>
<p><ul> 
<li> The Census Bureau states that American births should remain at about 3.9 million per year thought the turn of the century.
<p>
<li> Roughly 17% of family income is spent on an infant under one year, as compared with 21% of family income in 1960.  (And day care wasn't even part of the spending equation in 1960!)
<p>
<li> Day care now accounts for 14% of total spending on an infant under one year.
<p>
<li> In 1960, average family income was $30,120  -- that was back when the usual family only had one parent working.  Of that salary, $6,203 was spent on an infant under one.  Today, the average family income -- with two parents working -- is $44, 800.  Of that amount, $7,610 is spent on an infant under one, according the Agriculture Department.
<p>
<li> In 1995,  the majority of spending per infant was spent on child care and food, with clothing and health care following.  In 1960, the majority was spent on food (Remember: day care was not even a consideration then), with health care and clothing following.
<p>
<li> According to Lifestyle Change Communications, here's a specific breakdown in first-year costs:
<P><table border=0 cellpadding=7 cellspacing=7>
<tr>
	<td><b>diapers</b></td><td><b>$570</b></td></tr>
	<tr>
	<td><b>nursery</b></td><td><b>$1,200</b></td></tr>
	<tr>
	<td><b>furniture</b></td><td><b>$995</b></td></tr>
	<tr>
	<td><b>bedding/bath</b></td><td><b>$223</b></td></tr>
	<tr>
	<td><b>toys</b></td><td><b>$199</b></td></tr></table>
</ul><p>
	Even though 48% of women are in the work force, as compared with 27% in 1960,  their families are still spending less in the first year, in terms of family income, than their parents spent on them back in 1960.  Any way you look at it, babies really are big business!
<p>
(NOTE: These statistics were compiled compliments of the Washington Post Business Section on 10/4/96.)
<p>
<b>--  <a href="/heritage/cyberbio.html">Karen Czarnecki Miller</a></b>
</blockquote><p>


<i><b>Important note: Anyone may read the contents of the  <A HREF="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/wgw-forum/ac/dispatch.cgi/thf-cyber/">Forums</a>. To post a 
message, you will need to <a href="/townhall/wgw-forum/ac/dispatch.cgi/_user/addForm/short">register</a>. </b></i>

<p>
<center>
