<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Discovery Inquiry</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H2><CENTER><I>1996 Discovery Inquiry Vol. IV, #1<BR>
</I></CENTER>
</H2>
<H1><CENTER><TT><BR>
Has the 21st Century Arrived?</TT></CENTER>
</H1>
<H4><CENTER>by<BR>
<I><A HREF="chapman.html">Bruce Chapman</A></I></CENTER>
</H4>
<IMG SRC="barrwb.gif" WIDTH="780" HEIGHT="6" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
It turns out that Jesus was really born about six B.C., not in the year
0, as you might expect. A sixth century monk named Dionysius Exiguus, who
was given responsibility for settling a dispute over the date of Easter,
miscalculated his account of Jesus' life and placed His birth about six
years late. This scholarly error, which was perpetuated in later calendars,
means that we already are in the 21st century, and, for that matter, in
the Third Millennium. <BR>
<BR>
There is a certain satisfaction in our unexpected arrival in the 21st century
and the new millennium, if only because it has caught the numerologists
off guard. It will be harder now for them to peddle their prognostications
when the merely nominal millennium rolls around. <BR>
<BR>
But the new century, if not the new millennium, already has begun intellectually,
too--and politically and culturally. Just as the fin de si&egrave;cle 100
years ago closed down the 19th century in a burst of fashionable despair
mixed with exciting new ideas about nature, man and society, we are now
witnessing rejection of many of the prevalent ideas of the 20th Century.
And again something new is coming onto the stage of history. <BR>
<BR>
What seems to be happening intellectually and politically is the cumulative
repudiation of the whole grim, pedantic, utopian, hedonistic-yet-moralizing,
centralizing, pyschologizing, determinist, reductionist, relativist, modernist
project of the 20th Century. And I say, good riddance! <BR>
What may replace it is a revitalized version of what used to be called the
liberal tradition of the West, facilitated by new science and new technology.
<H3><BR>
<BR>
The Case Against the 20th Century </H3>
<BR>
<BR>
Of course, there was some good to the 20th century, and some necessary change.
For example, we probably did need a civil service to replace the political
spoils system--though we later got carried away and let bureaucracies regulate
away many of our freedoms. We did need civil rights protection through central
government action in order, finally, to right the great wrong of slavery
and to fulfill the spirit of the Declaration of Independence. But the best
intellectual innovations of the 20th century were in the fields of science
and technology--medicine and communications, notably. Most of the others
were of lesser significance or were baneful. <BR>
<BR>
Not only did the 20th century bring us the scourges of fascism and communism,
but, to a lesser degree, it brought us what the Alexis de Tocqueville correctly
foresaw as the &quot;democratic tyrannies&quot; of socialism and the welfare
state. Specialization and expertise flourished, bringing great benefits
in some areas, but also contributing to the depreciation of the liberal
arts. Over-emphasis on expertise also tempted leaders in one field to claim
authority in others, which is always a moral usurpation. Some generalists,
in turn, claimed the label of science for arts and crafts that did not deserve
it. This holds true for several of the &quot;social sciences,&quot; but
especially for something that grandly calls itself &quot;political science.&quot;
Even economics claimed more scientific stature than it deserved, guided
by the late 20th century conceit that the qualitative can always be quantified.
What the experts and pseudo-experts did was separate ordinary people from
their government and culture, robbing their authority and undermining their
morale. <BR>
<BR>
Not only was the authority of representative democracy undermined, but so,
too, was God's. It was the century that popularized the &quot;God is Dead&quot;
movement and--professing &quot;science&quot; again--tried to free us from
what modernists considered the superstition of religion. We actually created
an official culture--not in Russia, but in the United States!--that frowns
on expressions of religious faith in public life. We even self-censor, making
faith a non-subject in leading private as well as public arenas. Most American
youth grow up without any grounding in religious faith, or take a naive
Sunday school faith into combat with sophisticated university debunkers.
<BR>
<BR>
We are a more materialist culture than ever before. But materialism itself
is deadening. It has created a great cyst of loss and sorrow in our collective
soul. <BR>
<BR>
Among elites, few are religious, or even seriously stoic. Instead, they
worship a kind of debonair high style, and, of course, they worship health.
For them, as Jackson Lears says in his history of advertising, salvation
equals peak performance in the bedroom, the bathroom and the boardroom (and,
one might add, the exercise room). <BR>
<BR>
But isn't it odd that this age of materialism has seen such an efflorescence
of real superstitions? They range from New Age channelers to cable channel
psychics charging $4 a minute. <BR>
<BR>
Spiritual demoralization -- the loss of moral bearings and morale -- affects
the way we raise families and conduct our work. The professions today, especiallay
law, medicine and teaching, already are infected by demoralization. So is
journalism, which adopts cynicism as a reflexive attitude. In turn, &quot;all
this cynicism has permeated society,&quot; says Queens University Professor
George Rawlyk in the Vancouver Sun, &quot;and caused people to lose faith
in institutions.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Politics is definitely demoralized. Bureaucrats and experts--including that
strange breed, the professional &quot;ethicist&quot;--have trod on the cord
of responsibility that links the elected official to the electorate. More
worrisome, young people know almost nothing of the system of representative
democracy and therefore are bored with it, when they are not disgusted.
<H3><BR>
<BR>
The False Promise of &quot;Reform&quot; </H3>
<BR>
<BR>
The so-called &quot;reform movement,&quot; once volunteer, but now professionalized,
aims to take the politics out of politics and replace it with juicy personal
scandals or mere titillating innuendo. Whereas the communists said the political
is personal, which made the state's role tyrannous, the present-day reformer
says the personal is political--and transforms the private gossip of politics
into subjects of public litigation. That is distracting, and it, too, can
become tyrannous. <BR>
<BR>
Over-regulating human life -- including public life -- destroys liberty.
When the laws governing politics become so voluminous and complex that no
one even knows whether he is in compliance or not, a candidate or office-holder
is at the mercy of anyone who investigates him. This is always the irony:
the more laws and regulations you have, the more inevitable lawbreaking
becomes. And, because everyone can be found to have broken some law, the
decision as to whom to prosecute becomes--once more--arbitrary. Yet it was
to resist the power of arbitrary authority that the rule of law was established.
<BR>
<BR>
When the current political reform movement gained sway about 25 years ago,
it was with the promise of restoring confidence in government. (I know,
I was a part of it.) But, all surveys show that public confidence actually
has fallen during the very period when reform laws have been enacted. <BR>
<BR>
Reform has become just another political weapon. Our experience is thus
an extreme recapitulation of the earlier reform period, the Progressive
Era, 100 years ago. Also starting with high ideals, a number of the progressives
ultimately descended into false and exaggerated accusations and personal
abuse of power. Theodore Roosevelt, himself a reformer, gave us the term
&quot;muckraker,&quot; borrowed from the low-visioned Man with the Muckrake
in Pilgrim's Progress. He could have been speaking of our own time when,
on another occasion, he remarked, &quot;Whoever said that 'Patriotism is
the last refuge of a scoundrel' had not considered the possibilities of
'reform.'&quot; 
<H3><BR>
<BR>
Birth of 20th Century Thinking </H3>
<BR>
<BR>
From where did the past century get such curious reversals of virtue and
vice? Well, much of the force of 20th century modernism, for good and ill
alike, developed from industrial era science and industrial era ideas. Without
succumbing to over-generalization, one can still point to telling patterns,
especially in the work of the great thinkers of the later 19th and early
20th centuries, and of their followers, whose influence still is with us.
Chief among them: Karl Marx, Frederick Nietzsche, Sigmund Freud, Charles
Darwin and Albert Einstein. <BR>
<BR>
Through such thinkers, science, which really did accomplish great things
in the past century, also was misused to create the materialist culture:
atheistic, relativist, and cynical about personal virtue, yet blithely prepared
to build a New Society. Marx, for example, gave us the term &quot;dialectical
materialism,&quot; the priority of matter over mind. He taught class warfare
as a just pursuit and assailed bourgeois morality. Like most social engineers,
he created a system where everyone was exposed as self- interested, except,
of course, for himself and his favorite abstraction, the workers. <BR>
<BR>
Nietzsche taught us the &quot;will-to-power,&quot; the claims of self-expression
and moral relativism beyond good and evil. On the extreme right he inspired
the Nazis. And yet he also was the progenitor of the New Left and the hippies
in the 1960s. Nietzsche taught that there is no God, but that you can be
a god. From deconstruction in academia to the cynicism of the media, his
effects seem as strong as ever today. <BR>
<BR>
Freud was another brilliant, single-minded simplifier whose perspective
reflected the industrial era in which he lived. To him, a person is like
a steam engine, full of tensions that have to be released--thrusting pistons
and opposing forces. It wasn't just his emphasis on sexuality that was exaggerated,
but also his willingness, and that of his followers, to misapply their gifted
insights into mental disorders to a wide range of other fields, including
religion, war, history, philosophy, art and literature. <BR>
<BR>
So far, Darwin has stood the test of time better. But the uses to which
his ideas have been put are another matter. He never wanted to apply natural
selection to human society, and yet, far right and left both made bold use
of Darwin's ideas to do just that. From Social Darwinism to National Socialism
to the view of man as a soulless animal, Darwinism has been used to justify
complete disregard of the poor, on one hand, and the practice of eugenics
and euthanasia on the other. How instructive it is that the little metal
fish symbols some Christians stick on their autos are now mocked on other
autos by little metal amphibians with &quot;Darwin&quot; written on them!
<BR>
<BR>
Einstein was locked into relativity (which, of course, is not to be confused
with relativism), a theory that explained certain relationships between
time and space, matter and energy. Einstein wanted physical laws that would
hold true anywhere. Most of his discoveries were made before 1906 and he
spent the rest of his life trying to disprove the uncertainty principle
at the foundation of quantum theory-still seeking a mechanistic explanation
for the universe. But he failed. What Heisenberg, Planck and, more recently,
Richard Feynman, revealed is that atoms cannot be deterministically defined,
and that at the heart of every atom are mysterious and infinite waves. In
other words, matter doesn't matter--at least not as much as we thought.
<BR>
<BR>
But if materialism, even in physics, no longer prevails how can it possibly
be used, as Marx and several other industrial-era thinkers (or their followers)
attempted, to define the life of the human mind and the organization of
society? 
<H3><BR>
<BR>
The Return of Freedom </H3>
<BR>
<BR>
The answer is that it cannot, and the good news is that this intellectual
realization is beginning to affect our social and political life. As much
as anything, the technological revolution that is built on the science of
quantum physics and probability theory, makes this clear. The silicon chip,
the computer, software, fiber optics, and wireless telephony are among the
great triumphs of mind over matter. The Industrial Age thus has given way
to the Information Age. The effects are seen not only in communications,
but in the broad economy, where work is being decentralized and personalized
and where intellectual property now competes in value with physical property.
<BR>
<BR>
The information revolution helped topple the Soviet Union, which could not
compete with American high technology and could not tolerate the openness
resulting from computers. Indeed, it could not resist the force of the new
technology in part because communism is a rigid, centralized, industrial-era
system. But the USSR and other command economies and political systems are
not the only ones threatened by the new information freedom model. So are
almost all overly centralized, bureaucratic organizations that operate the
way they did in industrial times. <BR>
<BR>
The revolution is now beginning to shake the earth under the U.S. federal
government. And other levels of government. And great universities. And
even the public school system. It is affecting our thinking about transportation
and the future of cities. <BR>
<BR>
New technologies are &quot;only&quot; tools, of course, but history shows
that once man creates new tools, the new tools tend to reshape the way man
lives. <BR>
<BR>
They surely will overthrow the contemporary version of television, the last
great example of industrial age technology. TV broadcasts from a central
point where all the power resides. It, too, is a top-down power structure.
You take what you get, and what you get is standardized, because it must
appeal to the lowest common denominator of a mass audience. The new technology
that is about to take its place- -including especially what George Gilder
calls the &quot;teleputer&quot;--will be interactive as well as multi-media.
It is a bottom-up power structure, liberated from the center, and free of
the potential for Orwellian propaganda controls found in industrial-era
communications. <BR>
<BR>
Leftists would have you believe it is elitist; it is not. You, as user,
will control it, selecting exactly what you want and when you want it. Videoconferencing,
family gatherings in cyberspace, new ways to learn exactly at the pace suitable
for you or your child, and choices tailored to what is individual and distinctive
about you: All these are designed to serve your own interests and pursuits,
not those prescribed for you. They will connect you to others near and far
who share those interests--say, pre-Columbian art or gardening or learning
a foreign language. Already the Internet is providing alternative sources
of political action and news. Some critics think it threatens to bring us
mass direct democracy, unscreened from temporary passions and runaway enthusiasms.
I believe it is more likely to help restore the authority of representative
democracy. <BR>
<BR>
The new communications technology both reflects the disintegration of materialist
assumptions and contributes to that disintegration, so the process is robust.
Nonetheless, we will long have to deal with the cultural and political detritus
left over from the collapse of the materialist dispensation. <BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, it is exactly among the educated elites that ideas of materialism
took strongest hold and it is also within those quarters that confusion
and uncertainty-- demoralization--is greatest. But the average citizen,
never having drunk as deep at the well of 20th century ideology as did the
elites, is not as ill-prepared for the 21st century. Ordinary people, surveys
show, still believe in God, still believe in objective right and wrong,
still credit common sense, human nature and a Jeffersonian, rather than
a deconstructionist, understanding of the Constitution and the Bill of Rights.
They even persist in the benighted, pre-20th century view that art has something
to do with beauty and truth. As the late Christopher Lasch put it, the early
20th century writer and critic Ortega y Gasset's fear has been proven wrong;
the &quot;masses&quot; did not revolt against western civilization, only
the elites did. <BR>
<BR>
And now many people seem to be revolting against the whole soft tyranny
of modernism. This is really the 18th and 19th century liberal tradition
reasserting itself for the 21st century. <BR>
<BR>
The term &quot;liberalism&quot; here, of course, is not the left fork that
political liberalism took in this century, but the older understanding of
a free and civil society--with its institutions of representative democracy,
limited government and freedom from arbitrary rule, belief in progress,
tolerance, emancipation from dogma, and individual rights coupled with personal
responsibility--all tutored by civic virtue. This tradition rebelled against
a state church, but in this country almost always presupposed a divine order.
<BR>
<BR>
This classical liberal tradition was the consensus tradition of the United
States, distinguishing us from the Old World order. As Thomas Jefferson
proclaimed after the bitter election of 1800, &quot;We are all federalists
and we are all republicans.&quot; In the 1950s this point was observed again
by the so-called &quot;consensus school&quot; of historians, including Louis
Hartz and Richard Hofstaedter. It was a point that Francis Fukuyama made
in his essay, &quot;The End of History,&quot; a few years ago. <BR>
<BR>
The old liberal tradition moves forward in harmony with the individualist,
free-market drive of the information revolution. It is in harmony, also,
with government's appropriate functions, so it does not reflexively denigrate
public service. It is the tradition so despised today by campus reactionaries
on the left, steeped as they are in the paradoxically anti-Western influence
of such Western rebels as Marx and Nietzsche. The liberal tradition survives
such assaults precisely because it is open and ready to learn from other
cultures. In this, it looks back to the rich moral and intellectual resources
of the liberal arts. <BR>
<BR>
Traditionally, the liberal arts have consisted of language, philosophy,
history, literature, mathematics and abstract science. These subjects help
a man or woman to reflect upon how to live one's life, how to learn and
to interpret change. In the information age, these subjects are more precious
than ever. For now, when one opts out of a liberal education and into mere
professionalism or tradecraft, he is both likely to find himself impoverished
mentally and rendered obsolescent by constantly changing technology. <BR>
<BR>
It is quite possible that we already have hit bottom in the disregard of
the liberal arts and are beginning to look up. A recent report, for example,
shows the study of the classics increasing on college campuses. At 28,000
students, classics enrollment is higher than it has been in almost 30 years.
The classics teach not only the dead languages of Latin and Ancient Greek,
but also the history and philosophy of the Greeks and Romans, and those
works are as vital as ever. Happily, they can betaught today with the aid
of CD- Roms. <BR>
<BR>
At the moment, what is called conservatism is the political movement most
congenial to revival and restatement of the liberal tradition for the 21st
century. One sees this in those state capitols where governors are exploring
new ways to hook social and economic policies to human nature rather than
to abstract, welfare-state ideals. One sees it in Congress where House Speaker
Newt Gingrich refuses to adhere to the barbarian caricature of his adversaries
but pursues a coherent and old/new fashioned restatement of the goals of
limited government--and with panache as well as vision. <BR>
<BR>
But, obviously, this great seachange cannot be confined to any one party,
let alone one figure. Many nominally on the political left today are intrigued
by the possibilities that new intellectual understandings and new technologies
can improve public policy in unanticipated ways. Indeed, they are influenced
by today's intellectual currents on the right in the same way, for example,
that the right in earlier times was influenced by the Progressive Era and
the New Deal. <BR>
<BR>
Regardless, much that until recently was unthinkable is now on the table.
We used to describe someone as &quot;so conservative he wants to privatize
the Post Office.&quot; Today, in the age of overnight courier services,
FAX machines and E- mail, privatization is taking place with hardly any
one noticing. Twenty years ago you could not find mention of the word &quot;privatization&quot;
in the lexicon of public policy. Now the loose consensus on the value of
privatizing many government activities stretches from the Republican right
to Chicago's Democratic Mayor Richard Daley. The call for decentralization
comes from governors of both parties. Democratic senators such as Bennett
Johnston (LA) and Wendell Ford (KY) join Slade Gorton (WA) and Dirk Kempthorne
(ID) in calling for the Endangered Species Act to be rewritten. Even President
Clinton indicates support for revisions, if not repudiation, of affirmative
action, and finds a whole host of leading black intellectuals, such as Thomas
Sowell, Shelby Steele, Stephen Carter, and Glenn Loury already there. <BR>
<BR>
When one side of the political spectrum starts to embrace the positions
and policies of the other, something profound is happening, not only to
politics but to the culture. <BR>
<BR>
I suggest that what is beginning to happen is the restoration of a noble
and correct view of the world. When Aristotle wrote his Politics and his
Ethics, he defined a way to determine what is good--the Golden Mean between
&quot;excess&quot; and &quot;defect.&quot; In specific application of those
absolute standards to a particular principle, however, man was to look to
consequences as well as to means, and employ prudence, the virtue of good
judgment. When it came to public philosophy, Jews and Christians found common
ground in such a moral philosophy, and undergirded it with revelation. Indeed,
as C.S. Lewis wrote, you do not requirereligion to find that common ground,
or, as he called it, the Tao. For God gave man reason, and through that
reason, most civilizations apprehend the Tao. 
<H3><BR>
<BR>
Untangling the Materialist Mind </H3>
<BR>
It wasn't simply materialism that failed, but utopianism, which is its contradictory
and yet complementary twin. The materialist/relativist tells us that there
are no normative standards; for example, the definition of a &quot;family&quot;
is anything you want it to be. (After all, you have your &quot;values&quot;
and I have mine.) The utopian impulse in the same modernist mind is much
sterner. When it comes to endangered species or product liability or sexual
harassment, it dictates absolute purity of means, as well as purposes. Thus,
on one hand, we have moral vagueness, and, on the other, rigidly moralistic
emphasis on processes. What both of these superficially dissimilar modernist
impulses--which normally co-habit--have in common is that neither looks
very much at consequences. <BR>
<BR>
In contrast, for the founders of the liberal tradition, the Greeks, the
object in politics as in life was not the triumph of one interest or one
consideration, but the balance, the harmony, of interests and considerations.
<BR>
<BR>
The American Founders also clearly stood in that line. The great goal of
the 21st Century, following the classical liberal tradition, is to recover
that sense of harmony in life--the sacred and the practical, private virtue
and civic virtue, and the personal in balance with the political.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
